% =====================================================================
\section{Discussion}
\label{sec:discussion}

\paragraph{Every abstraction lever is speed, not capacity.}
Across the full ladder --- representational, behavioral, temporal, and
hierarchy-depth --- abstraction lowers the \emph{statistical / optimization} cost
of reaching a ceiling that a strong flat baseline also reaches; it does not raise
that ceiling. This is the unifying claim, now established across abstraction
\emph{types} (Bet 1) and \emph{up the hierarchy} (Bet 2). It reframes ``does
abstraction help?'' as axis-dependent: yes on speed-of-learning, no on asymptote.

\paragraph{Why the information term is often already satisfied.}
A value-sufficient SimNorm latent already satisfies the information / anti-collapse
objective that a JEPA must enforce, which is \emph{why} an added SE/abstraction
term is redundant --- a worked instance of ``when is the information term already
satisfied?'' The structural-entropy surrogate is motivated, not as a solution to
the McAllester--Stratos impossibility, but as a tractable, assumption-light
\emph{structural} proxy where the statistical route is provably hard.

\paragraph{The Director caveat.}
Our hierarchy GO is on a \emph{non-generative} latent, but
Director~\citep{hafner2022director} shows generative latent world models already
do competitive hierarchical latent planning. So LeCun's generativity sub-claim is
not adjudicated by our experiment. We frame our result as \emph{testing} the bet;
the Director-style baseline (\S\ref{sec:results-hier}) is required before any
claim that a non-generative abstract latent is necessary.

\paragraph{Limits.}
(i) The hierarchy test uses a bounded 2-level subgoal/skill hierarchy on existing
infrastructure as the \emph{minimal decisive test}; a true differentiable
multi-level H-JEPA with subgoal emission is a multi-week effort and remains future
work. (ii) Long-horizon manipulation has physical/kinematic ceilings (the
${\sim}0.83$ PickCube ceiling is physical), so we measure speed to a reachable
threshold, not the ceiling. (iii) The entity-graph OOD result and several
graph-side measurements are single-seed / synthetic with documented caveats.
(iv) The crowded 2026 JEPA-derivative space requires a fresh related-work sweep at
submission. \todo{run the submission-time related-work sweep over 2602/2603 arXiv
stems; do not cite post-cutoff derivatives without verification.}

% =====================================================================
\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

We reframed a decade of inconsistent ``does abstraction help?'' results as an
axis mismatch: the field scores asymptotic return, whereas LeCun's world-model
program and Chollet's measure of intelligence both argue the right axis is speed
of learning. Decomposing LeCun's program into a metric bet and an architecture
bet, we tested both under one matched-control, speed-of-learning protocol. The
metric bet is confirmed: representational, behavioral, and temporal abstraction
are null on asymptote and real only on sample-efficiency. The architecture bet is
a qualified GO: hierarchy depth and subgoal horizon are genuine speed levers, yet
no hierarchical arm lifts the asymptotic ceiling and the depth advantage itself
dissolves at $2\times$ budget. Every abstraction lever we tested buys speed, not
capacity. The decisive remaining test --- a Director-style generative-hierarchy
baseline --- is pending.

